{environment->public_information}
Your private busy slots and preferences:
{agents->helen->private_information}
Your goal:
{agents->helen->goal}
Respond with a structured summary of your availability for Monday within the work hours {environment->init->work_hours->start} to {environment->init->work_hours->end}, listing free time intervals in the format [{"start":"HH:MM","end":"HH:MM"}, ...]. Respect the stated preference (do not propose times after 13:30 if you indicate that preference). Do not produce PDDL. If information is missing, only report what you know.

pddl.prompt:
You are the orchestrator. Use the public information about the task:
{environment->public_information}
Meeting parameters:
Day: {environment->init->day}
Work hours: {environment->init->work_hours->start} to {environment->init->work_hours->end}
Meeting duration (minutes): {environment->init->meeting_duration_minutes}
Here are the availability summaries provided by the participants:
{availability_margaret}
{availability_donna}
{availability_helen}
Your goal:
{agents->orchestrator->goal}
Task: Integrate the participants' availability outputs and produce a complete PDDL domain and a PDDL problem for FastDownwards that models time slots (or discrete 30-minute slots) and assigns a single 30-minute meeting slot where all three participants are free and Helen's preference is respected. Keep participant actions distinct if representing them as separate agents in the problem. Enclose the PDDL domain between <domain></domain> tags and the PDDL problem between <problem></problem> tags. Also include, as comments inside the PDDL or immediately after the <problem> tag, the human-readable chosen meeting time for convenience.
